# .NET 8 Migration: EventProcessor

## Key Issues with the Original Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8 — it was removed entirely.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` is obsolete** and throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8+.
3. **Race condition**: Multiple enqueues between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose items (only one dequeue per signal).
4. **No graceful shutdown** mechanism.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Failed to enqueue item.");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();            // signals no more items
        _cts?.Cancel();                        // cancels if stuck waiting
        if (_processingTask is not null)
            await _processingTask.ConfigureAwait(false);
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // processing logic here
    }
}
```

## If You Need a Synchronous/Thread-Based Approach

```csharp
using System.Collections.Concurrent;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts!.Token))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* expected on shutdown */ }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();       // no more items
        _cts?.Cancel();                // unblock if waiting
        _thread?.Join(5000);           // wait for clean exit
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { }
}
```

## Migration Pitfalls Summary

| .NET Framework Pattern | .NET 8 Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | Abort throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` | Obsolete, throws in .NET 8 |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` | Thread-safe, no lost signals |
| Manual thread lifecycle | `Task.Run` + `async/await` | Simpler, integrates with async ecosystem |
| No shutdown signal | `CancellationTokenSource` | Cooperative cancellation is the standard pattern |

## Recommendation

Prefer the **`Channel<T>`** approach — it's allocation-efficient, backpressure-aware, and idiomatic for .NET 8 producer/consumer patterns. Use `BlockingCollection<T>` only if you must stay synchronous (e.g., real-time audio/game loops where `async` overhead matters).
